The American Express Centurion Lounge at Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport, which had been eagerly awaited by travelers throughout the year, has failed its recent health inspection with a score of just 69.

The inspection, conducted by local health authorities, revealed several violations that led to the lounge‚Äôs low score. Among the cited issues were uncovered food items, which pose a risk of contamination, an unclean ice machine, which could compromise beverage safety, and the presence of flies near the bar area, indicating potential pest control problems.

This development has raised concerns among frequent flyers and airport visitors who had looked forward to the luxury and exclusivity promised by the Centurion Lounge. American Express officials have not yet responded to requests for comment on the inspection results or on what steps will be taken to address these health and safety issues.

Local health officials have emphasized the importance of maintaining high hygiene standards in public spaces, especially in high-traffic areas like airports. They have indicated that follow-up inspections will be conducted to ensure compliance with health regulations.

Travelers are advised to stay informed on the status of the lounge before planning to visit. Meanwhile, the airport authority has assured the public that they are committed to upholding the health and safety standards across all facilities within Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport.

Denver International Airport is on track to reach 100 million passengers annually by 2027, years ahead of schedule. Vision 100, the airport‚Äôs strategic plan to reach that number ahead of its 50th anniversary in 2045, originally planned to hit the mark between 2030 and 2035.

The boost in travelers has made DIA the 6th busiest airport in the world behind Dallas-Fort Worth, London Heathrow, Tokyo International, Dubai International, and Atlanta Hartsfield-Jackson International airports. 

However, it appears that the rapid growth has also resulted in fewer satisfied customers. A J.D. Power survey shows DIA ranked 12th out of 20 mega airports in 2024, falling five slots from 2023. That annual survey looks at six factors: terminal facilities; arrival/departure areas; baggage claim; security check; check-in/baggage check; and food, beverage and retail.

Learn more about the good, the bad and the growing pains at our link in bio.
